93834.name: Value of global exports as a share of world GDP (CEPII (2016))
93834.description: The global value of exports, by country, as a share of world GDP.

source.dataPublisherSource: IMF Direction of Trade Statistics data set, manuscripts
source.additionalInfo:
To calculate country exports to the rest of the world, the total value of exports by country, per year, is divided by the country's GDP. 

The time series 'World' corresponds to the World's total exports to the rest of the world. The total exports to the World consist of country exports in the sample summed together, then divided by the world GDP for the same year, and multiplied by 100. World GDP is the sum of all countries' GDP for a particular year. 

The total export values of regional income aggregates as a share of world GDP have been calculated using the World Bank's income groupings. The World Bank has four income classifications: High income, Upper-middle income, Lower-middle income, and Low income. The total value of exported goods for High income countries, for example, sums together the export values for countries belonging to this income classification, by year. This is then divided by World GDP, calculated by summing together all countries' GDP for a particular year. 

The value of global exports as a share of GDP have also been calculated for OWID continental groupings. Again, the total value of exports are summed together for each continent, for each year, which are then divided by World GDP. 

Germany's time series is comprised of West Germany, and Germany. East Germany has been excluded for the purposes of Germany's calculations.
Russia's time series comprises Russia and the USSR.
